00:04:14.330 --> 00:04:15.940
It's a traditional Thai dish.

00:04:15.940 --> 00:04:18.730
Actually, we had this
recipe at the restaurant,

00:04:18.730 --> 00:04:22.480
but it kind of morphed
to a home-cooked meal.

00:04:25.060 --> 00:04:27.460
Usually it's called [THAI].

00:04:27.460 --> 00:04:31.300
It's made with candied pork,
green beans, homemade chili

00:04:31.300 --> 00:04:33.460
paste, oyster sauce, sugar.

00:04:33.460 --> 00:04:36.050
That's very, very simple.

00:04:36.050 --> 00:04:40.910
The question you might ask
is, how did we get to bacon?

00:04:40.910 --> 00:04:43.750
So the story about
the bacon part,

00:04:43.750 --> 00:04:46.960
which I'm going to
start and get going--

00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:52.035
growing up in Oakland,
we were on welfare.

00:04:52.035 --> 00:04:54.670
So food stamps is
how we survived

00:04:54.670 --> 00:04:58.030
and how we fed ourselves.

00:04:58.030 --> 00:05:00.670
And with food stamps,
you were limited

00:05:00.670 --> 00:05:04.090
to what you can buy
at the grocery stores.

00:05:04.090 --> 00:05:07.950
And that's when I was
introduced to Oscar Mayer bacon.

00:05:07.950 --> 00:05:16.160
And instead of candied pork,
bacon was the substitute.

00:05:16.160 --> 00:05:17.689
Is it on?

00:05:17.689 --> 00:05:18.730
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: Fans.

00:05:18.730 --> 00:05:20.242
Thank you.

00:05:20.242 --> 00:05:21.700
JAMES SYHABOUT: So
that's how bacon

00:05:21.700 --> 00:05:23.060
was the substitute for that.

00:05:23.060 --> 00:05:28.160
So just like a lot of
the recipes in the book,

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:30.970
it's not meant to be authentic.

00:05:30.970 --> 00:05:35.710
It's kind of a filtration
of traditional dishes

00:05:35.710 --> 00:05:38.990
that got adapted to our
living situation in Oakland

00:05:38.990 --> 00:05:43.310
back from when we
were growing up.

00:05:43.310 --> 00:05:46.520
These are just Blue
Lake green beans.

00:05:46.520 --> 00:05:50.010
Just pick off the stem end.

00:05:50.010 --> 00:05:53.050
And you're just going to
deep fry ahead of time.

00:05:53.050 --> 00:05:54.740
And you can leave
this at room temp.

00:06:00.476 --> 00:06:03.450
The oil's about 375 degrees.

00:06:03.450 --> 00:06:06.990
It's a very, very quick fry,
just enough for the skin

00:06:06.990 --> 00:06:10.240
to blister and crinkle
up, but still remains

00:06:10.240 --> 00:06:13.449
a good crunch and texture.

00:06:13.449 --> 00:06:14.740
Throw the rest of them in here.

00:06:18.308 --> 00:06:20.869
It's a fairly
quick, easy recipe.

00:06:25.710 --> 00:06:28.796
At the restaurants that we
served at, we didn't use bacon.

00:06:28.796 --> 00:06:32.140
[LAUGHS] We used just
sliced pork that's

00:06:32.140 --> 00:06:34.620
been cooked down
with sugar and water

00:06:34.620 --> 00:06:38.210
until the water and the juice
of the pork's completely dry.

00:06:38.210 --> 00:06:41.790
And then the sugar caramelizes
and caramelizes itself.

00:06:41.790 --> 00:06:47.200
But at home, time was an issue.

00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:51.810
So my mother didn't
know what bacon was.

00:06:51.810 --> 00:06:54.450
And she knew it was a pork
product and it was pork belly.

00:06:54.450 --> 00:06:58.140
And she grabbed a package
of Oscar Mayer bacon

00:06:58.140 --> 00:07:01.380
and started making this at home.

00:07:01.380 --> 00:07:07.880
And actually, the very first
time I actually had this dish

00:07:07.880 --> 00:07:08.880
was with the bacon.

00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:09.880
So I didn't know better.

00:07:09.880 --> 00:07:11.830
I didn't know where
she was coming from.

00:07:11.830 --> 00:07:15.430
I never had the
traditional way until we

00:07:15.430 --> 00:07:16.907
opened our restaurants.

00:07:19.729 --> 00:07:20.520
That's good enough.

00:07:20.520 --> 00:07:22.690
I'm going to get all of it out.

00:07:22.690 --> 00:07:25.220
So we'll just push
this to the back.

00:07:25.220 --> 00:07:28.410
So the beans can sit chill
out for a little bit.

00:07:33.230 --> 00:07:34.460
I like this.

00:07:34.460 --> 00:07:35.064
This is cool.

00:07:35.064 --> 00:07:36.980
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: You
can ask me to do this.

00:07:36.980 --> 00:07:39.902
